@NODE intro "Introduction"

 
 A while ago, I didn't have any kind of unarchiver, and I was really fed up
 having to do it manually all the time.
 
 After a while, I thought to myself "Why don't I do one myself!", and this
 is how ArcExtract was born. a few weeks after that, I got a modem, and I
 realised that there were loads more programs than this one, but anyway.
 Maybe I'll make a better version some time in the future.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE req "System Requirements"

 Doesn't really need much, but here is what you need:
 
             
             - OS2+
             - ReqTools library
             - PowerPacker.library
             - XEN.font for the XEN setting
             - Archives?
             
@ENDNODE

@NODE install "Installing"

 Simply click on the Install icon supplied with this package.
 
 NOTE: The install script needs the Standard Escom Installer. If you do
 not have the installer, all you have to do is copy the ArcExtract drawer
 across to the desired destination and then copy the libraries to the LIBS:
 drawer on your system.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE usage "Using ArcExtract"

 Using ArcExtract under OS2+ is the simplest form. All you have to do is
 click on the icon. If you haven't used it before, it will ask you for an
 output path. Select where you want it to go, and it will save that path
 as a tool type for future use.
 
 When ever you want to extract a file, simply drag it to the AppIcon and
 when the message "Done!" comes up, it will have extracted to the selected
 path.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE prefs "Preferences"

 The Preferences window is very simple. There is an option for telling the
 program where it's going to extract all its files. Simply choose the path
 where you usually UnArchive your programs, eg - RAM:
 
 The Output Window option is for seeing the archivers Output window. Not
 Really useful, but if you like to see what files are being extracted,
 simply select this option. This option is highly recommened!!! Within
  the output Window(s), you can also put the Info Window in. This
  replaces the Percentage bar. The Info Window is much better than the bar.
 
 Icon X positions is the X position in Workbench where the icon will come up
 at the start.
 
 Icon Y Position is the same as above, except it determines where the Y
 position will come up.
 
 AppIcon Name is the name of the Icon. You can now change this, so it can
 say whatever you feel like it to say.

 The XEN setting is a new option which makes the Preferences interface use
 The XEN.font which is a nicer font than topaz.font. This setting is 
 especially good for Interlace users.
 
 'Sniffer' Mode is a brand new option. This is perhaps one of the best
 aspects of ArcExtract. If you don't have this setting on, it realies on
 file extenions (.lha, .lzx, etc). But, if you tick this box, it will
 actually read the file, and then work out what file type it is. There is
 however one disadvantage with this option. There are less @{ "Arc Types" link arc}
 supported with this option.
 
 If you activate the Output Window option, you will be able to customise
 what your Output Window is like. It is all pretty obvious, apart perhaps
 for the name. The standard Output window is a CON:, but you can have other
 type, like KCON: and others, which make it look better.

 


 The prefernces data is saved as: Sys:Prefs/Presets/ArcExtract.prefs

@ENDNODE

